min-height: 180px;\"><a class=\"viewableObjectLink\" href=\"#/shows/event-details/422\"><h5 class=\"title\">\"The Rock\" Asteroid</h5></a></div></div><p class=\"latest-news\">We've curated a catalog of our members' favorite objects and events in the night sky which we call the Slooh 500. These are the best looking objects to see through our telescopes which also have the most interesting folklore created in their name. Our community forms around them.</p></div><div class=\"promo-message-band\"><h4 class=\"title\">A Sampling of Slooh Community Content</h4></div><div class=\"telescope-block community-perspectives\"><div class=\"content\"><div class=\"row\"><ul class=\"col-xs-12 clearfix categories\"><li class=\"col-xs-3 category\"><a class=\"action active\" href=\"#/\" id=\"SCIENCE_LOG\"><p class=\"title\">Science log</p><div class=\"icon action active\" style=\"-webkit-mask-image: url(&quot;https://vega.slooh.com/icons/community/science_log.svg&quot;);\"></div></a></li><li class=\"col-xs-3 category\"><a class=\"action\" href=\"#/\" id=\"ART_CULTURE\"><p class=\"title\">Art &amp; culture</p><div class=\"icon action\" style=\"-webkit-mask-image: url(&quot;https://vega.slooh.com/icons/community/art_culture.svg&quot;);\"></div></a></li><li class=\"col-xs-3 category\"><a class=\"action\" href=\"#/\" id=\"HUMAN_SPIRIT\"><p class=\"title\">Human spirit</p><div class=\"icon action\" style=\"-webkit-mask-image: url(&quot;https://vega.slooh.com/icons/community/human_spirit.svg&quot;);\"></div></a></li><li class=\"col-xs-3 category\"><a class=\"action\" href=\"#/\" id=\"DIY\"><p class=\"title\">diy</p><div class=\"icon action\" style=\"-webkit-mask-image: url(&quot;https://vega.slooh.com/icons/community/DIY.svg&quot;);\"></div></a></li></ul><div class=\"col-xs-12\"><div class=\"col-xs-12 double-border\"></div></div><div class=\"col-xs-12 slide-container\"><div class=\"slick-initialized slick-slider slide\"><div class=\"slick-list\"><div class=\"slick-track\" style=\"opacity: 1; transform: translate3d(0px, 0px, 0px); width: 4723.33px;\"><div data-index=\"0\" class=\"slick-slide slick-active\" tabindex=\"-1\" style=\"outline: none; width: 363.333px;\"><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"item-header\"><div class=\"slooh-by-user-tag\"><div class=\"profile-photo\" style=\"background-image: url(&quot;https://vega.slooh.com/icons/placeholders/avatar-dummy.png&quot;);\"></div><div class=\"profile-name\"><h4 class=\"username\"><!-- react-text: 257 -->BrianV.2016<!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 258 --> <!-- /react-text --><span class=\"account-level\">Apprentice</span><br><span class=\"user-details dark\"><!-- react-text: 262 --><!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 263 --> Member since <!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 264 -->2016<!-- /react-text --></span></h4></div></div><button class=\"heart light\"><i class=\"fa fa-heart\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i><span class=\"count\">0</span><!-- react-empty: 268 --></button></div><div class=\"description\"><a class=\"descriptionLink\" href=\"#/community/post/3480\"><h3 class=\"title\"><span>A Dying Star in the Velvet Cluster</span></h3></a><div class=\"desc\"><p>The Velvet Cluster, M46, in the constellation Puppis is a worthy target in its own right for observers with binoculars or a small telescope. But this rich and bright open star cluster harbors a delight for sharp-eyed stargazers: a planetary nebula, the rarefied remnants of a dying Sun-like star.\n\nYou can see the tiny planetary nebula, NGC 2438, along the northern edge of the star cluster. It’s about 1’ across (or 1/60th of a degree), large enough to see in a small telescope at moderate magnification of 70x to 100x. A filter that cuts down on the effects of light pollution can also help you spot the nebula.\n\nBut is this planetary nebula actually in M46? Astronomers once suspected the nebula was associated with the star cluster, and there has been some back and forth among researchers over the years. But recent studies show the nebula is not moving with the same speed and direction as the stars in M46. It appears to be a foreground object along the same line of sight.\n\nStill, the view of a planetary nebula superimposed on an open star cluster is a rare sight in the heavens. So have a look for this chance alignment with your own scope on the next clear night.</p></div></div></div></div><div data-index=\"1\" class=\"slick-slide slick-active\" tabindex=\"-1\" style=\"outline: none; width: 363.333px;\"><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"item-header\"><div class=\"slooh-by-user-tag\"><div class=\"profile-photo\" style=\"background-image: url(&quot;https://vega.slooh.com/icons/placeholders/avatar-dummy.png&quot;);\"></div><div class=\"profile-name\"><h4 class=\"username\"><!-- react-text: 282 -->BrianV.2016<!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 283 --> <!-- /react-text --><span class=\"account-level\">Apprentice</span><br><span class=\"user-details dark\"><!-- react-text: 287 --><!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 288 --> Member since <!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 289 -->2016<!-- /react-text --></span></h4></div></div><button class=\"heart light\"><i class=\"fa fa-heart\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i><span class=\"count\">0</span><!-- react-empty: 293 --></button></div><div class=\"description\"><a class=\"descriptionLink\" href=\"#/community/post/3541\"><h3 class=\"title\"><span>The Horsehead Nebula</span></h3></a><div class=\"desc\"><p>Near the star Alnitak, the easternmost star in Orion’s Belt, lies the Horsehead Nebula, one of the most recognizable assemblies in the heavens. While it’s far fainter than the famous Orion Nebula in the Sword of Orion, and therefore much more difficult to see, the nebula is&nbsp;a delight for astrophotographers and armchair stargazers and one of the best examples of a cloud of dark and sooty interstellar dust superimposed on a bright background of glowing hydrogen&nbsp;gas.\n\nThe glowing reddish-pink region in the background of the Horsehead Nebula is cataloged by astronomers as IC 434. Like the Orion Nebula, IC 434 is an emission nebula, a gas cloud powered by a&nbsp;blazing-hot star. Etched against the glowing IC 434 is the chess-piece&nbsp;outline of the dark nebula Barnard 33 (B33). This is one of more than three hundred dark clouds of gas and fine dust discovered by Edward Emerson Barnard, the prodigious and self-made American astronomer who rose from abject poverty after the American Civil War to become the most astute professional observer and astrophotographer of the early 20th century.\n\nDark nebulae are common throughout the spiral arms of the Milky Way. But B33 lies in the foreground of the reddish-pink emission nebula so it stands out very clearly. This dark nebula itself is an eddy of gas and dust, swirling at some 20 km/s. Within the nebula, small pockets are slowly collapsing to form more stars. But most of the nebula will be blown away by the gentle but steady pressure of ultraviolet light from massive new stars over the next 5 million years.\n\nThe sooty appearance of the dark Horsehead is a result of tenuous clouds of of carbon-based molecules and dust grains flecked through the nebula. Within the Horsehead and dark regions of the Orion Nebula, radio astronomers have detected molecules such as water, ethyl alcohol, ammonia, sulphur dioxide, methanol, and dozens of others. As clumps of the nebula coalesce into new stars and solar systems, some of these molecules may find their way onto the surface of small bodies like comets, asteroids, and even planets.</p></div></div></div></div><div data-index=\"2\" class=\"slick-slide slick-active\" tabindex=\"-1\" style=\"outline: none; width: 363.333px;\"><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"item-header\"><div class=\"slooh-by-user-tag\"><div class=\"profile-photo\" style=\"background-image: url(&quot;https://vega.slooh.com/icons/placeholders/avatar-dummy.png&quot;);\"></div><div class=\"profile-name\"><h4 class=\"username\"><!-- react-text: 307 -->BrianV.2016<!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 308 --> <!-- /react-text --><span class=\"account-level\">Apprentice</span><br><span class=\"user-details dark\"><!-- react-text: 312 --><!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 313 --> Member since <!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 314 -->2016<!-- /react-text --></span></h4></div></div><button class=\"heart light\"><i class=\"fa fa-heart\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i><span class=\"count\">1</span><!-- react-empty: 318 --></button></div><div class=\"description\"><a class=\"descriptionLink\" href=\"#/community/post/3478\"><h3 class=\"title\"><span>The M81 Galaxy Group</span></h3></a><div class=\"desc\"><p>In the months of late winter and early spring in the northern hemisphere, stargazers with a small telescope can tour the brightest members of the M81 Galaxy Group, one of the nearest congregations of galaxies to the Milky Way. \n\nThe M81 Group takes its name from the majestic ‘grand design’ spiral galaxy M81, also called Bode’s Galaxy, the biggest spiral in the group and its gravitational anchor. This big spiral recently brushed by its neighboring galaxy and fellow group member M82 (the Cigar Galaxy) and triggered an intense burst of star formation. Other brighter members of the M81 Galaxy Group include the lovely spiral NGC 2403, the peculiar elliptical galaxy NGC 3077, and the barred spiral NGC 4236. All rank among the favorite targets of many experienced stargazers and astrophotographers.\n\nLike our own Local Cluster of Galaxies, which includes the Milky Way, the Andromeda Galaxy, and the Triangulum Galaxy, the M81 Group is a member of the Virgo Supercluster, one of the millions of galaxy superclusters that fleck the universe.</p></div></div></div></div><div data-index=\"3\" class=\"slick-slide\" tabindex=\"-1\" style=\"outline: none; width: 363.333px;\"><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"item-header\"><div class=\"slooh-by-user-tag\"><div class=\"profile-photo\" style=\"background-image: url(&quot;https://vega.slooh.com/icons/placeholders/avatar-dummy.png&quot;);\"></div><div class=\"profile-name\"><h4 class=\"username\"><!-- react-text: 332 -->BrianV.2016<!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 333 --> <!-- /react-text --><span class=\"account-level\">Apprentice</span><br><span class=\"user-details dark\"><!-- react-text: 337 --><!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 338 --> Member since <!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 339 -->2016<!-- /react-text --></span></h4></div></div><button class=\"heart light\"><i class=\"fa fa-heart\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i><span class=\"count\">0</span><!-- react-empty: 343 --></button></div><div class=\"description\"><a class=\"descriptionLink\" href=\"#/community/post/3494\"><h3 class=\"title\"><span>Will All Stars Become Supernovae?</span></h3></a><div class=\"desc\"><p>A core-collapse supernova is one of the most energetic and violent events in the universe, releasing&nbsp;as much energy in a few weeks as an entire galaxy. So they understandably get a lot of press. But only the biggest and rarest stars have a chance of becoming a supernova. Stars like our Sun, and those up to about&nbsp;eight solar masses, will end their lives in a less spectacular fashion by gently&nbsp;blowing off their outer layers as&nbsp;a planetary nebula and leaving their cores behind as a white dwarf star. Bigger stars, however, keep burning their store of fuel in the core until energy can no longer be generated, and the star collapses suddenly and explodes outward leaving behind a neutron star or, in some cases, a black hole. That’s what a supernova is all about.\n\nIn our galaxy, a big star explodes as a supernova every 50-100 years, on average. We’re due for one: the last observable supernova in the Milky Way happened in 1604. But with the help of big telescopes, astronomers discover a few dozen supernovae each year in other galaxies. And&nbsp;there are so many galaxies in the observable universe, astronomers estimate some 30 stars explode as a supernova every SECOND! The universe is a big place…</p></div></div></div></div><div data-index=\"4\" class=\"slick-slide\" tabindex=\"-1\" style=\"outline: none; width: 363.333px;\"><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"item-header\"><div class=\"slooh-by-user-tag\"><div class=\"profile-photo\" style=\"background-image: url(&quot;https://vega.slooh.com/icons/placeholders/avatar-dummy.png&quot;);\"></div><div class=\"profile-name\"><h4 class=\"username\"><!-- react-text: 357 -->BrianV.2016<!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 358 --> <!-- /react-text --><span class=\"account-level\">Apprentice</span><br><span class=\"user-details dark\"><!-- react-text: 362 --><!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 363 --> Member since <!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 364 -->2016<!-- /react-text --></span></h4></div></div><button class=\"heart light\"><i class=\"fa fa-heart\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i><span class=\"count\">2</span><!-- react-empty: 368 --></button></div><div class=\"description\"><a class=\"descriptionLink\" href=\"#/community/post/3477\"><h3 class=\"title\"><span>M82 – A Starburst Galaxy</span></h3></a><div class=\"desc\"><p>Just off the bowl of the Big Dipper lies Messier 82, an edge-on spiral galaxy wracked by an intense burst of star formation. Also called the Cigar Galaxy, M82 is visible in a small telescope, and even a good pair of binoculars in dark sky.\n\nAt a distance of 12 million light years, M82 is the nearest example of a starburst galaxy. A recent tidal interaction with its large and stately neighboring galaxy M81 triggered an intense burst of star formation about a hundred million years ago. Stars form in M82 at a rate ten times as fast as in the Milky Way.\n\nThe immense light output from these stars means M82 outshines our entire galaxy by a factor of five, and the core of the galaxy is an astonishing one hundred times brighter than the core of our Milky Way. Near the core of M82, nearly two hundred clusters of massive new stars have recently formed, each with the mass of 200,000 suns. These stars eject plumes of glowing hydrogen gas which is visible in detailed images as fingers of reddish light emerging from the core. Stargazers on a planet in the spiral arms of M82 would have a view of thousands of brilliant stars in their night sky.\n\nThe frenzied rate of star formation in M82 can’t last forever. In a few tens of millions of years, all the gas available for star formation will be used up, and star formation will come to an end.</p></div></div></div></div><div data-index=\"5\" class=\"slick-slide\" tabindex=\"-1\" style=\"outline: none; width: 363.333px;\"><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"item-header\"><div class=\"slooh-by-user-tag\"><div class=\"profile-photo\" style=\"background-image: url(&quot;https://vega.slooh.com/icons/placeholders/avatar-dummy.png&quot;);\"></div><div class=\"profile-name\"><h4 class=\"username\"><!-- react-text: 382 -->BrianV.2016<!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 383 --> <!-- /react-text --><span class=\"account-level\">Apprentice</span><br><span class=\"user-details dark\"><!-- react-text: 387 --><!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 388 --> Member since <!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 389 -->2016<!-- /react-text --></span></h4></div></div><button class=\"heart light\"><i class=\"fa fa-heart\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i><span class=\"count\">0</span><!-- react-empty: 393 --></button></div><div class=\"description\"><a class=\"descriptionLink\" href=\"#/community/post/3491\"><h3 class=\"title\"><span>Sirius B – A White Dwarf Star</span></h3></a><div class=\"desc\"><p>In the early 19th century, the great astronomer Friedrich Bessel&nbsp;noticed a remarkable think about the star Sirius– it seemed to wobble as it slowly moved across the sky. This back-and-forth motion was a result of a hidden star that was extremely faint but had enough mass to tug on its slightly larger and much brighter companion. This little star was named&nbsp;Sirius B, &nbsp;and because it follows Sirius A, the Dog Star, through the sky, it’s sometimes simply called &nbsp;the ‘Pup’.\n\nBinary stars like Sirius A and B are quite common. But astronomers were perplexed by the Pup. It was hotter than our Sun, hot enough to shine with a whitish color like Sirius A, and it was roughly as massive as the Sun. But the Pup&nbsp;was very faint, which meant it must be only about as large as the Earth. Astronomers came to call such stars ‘white dwarfs’. In time, they discovered dozens, then hundreds, then thousands&nbsp;of these strange little stars through the 19th century and into modern times.\n\nWe know now a white dwarf star is a remnant from an old star that’s run out of fuel in its core and ejected its outer layers as a planetary nebula. In fact, a white dwarf IS the core of the old star, hot and dense and made of carbon and oxygen, mostly, with a thin outer layer of hydrogen and helium gas. The star no longer generates its own energy. It will simple cool, like a hot piece of coal, until all the heat is radiated away into space over tens of billions of years.\n\nAll white dwarfs share one key feature: they all have a mass less than 1.4 solar masses. If mass is added to a white dwarf, say from a nearby companion star, so that it exceeds this limit, the white dwarf&nbsp;will collapse and explode as a nova or even a supernova depending on the details and geometry of the system.\n\n&nbsp;</p></div></div></div></div><div data-index=\"6\" class=\"slick-slide\" tabindex=\"-1\" style=\"outline: none; width: 363.333px;\"><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"item-header\"><div class=\"slooh-by-user-tag\"><div class=\"profile-photo\" style=\"background-image: url(&quot;https://vega.slooh.com/icons/placeholders/avatar-dummy.png&quot;);\"></div><div class=\"profile-name\"><h4 class=\"username\"><!-- react-text: 407 -->BrianV.2016<!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 408 --> <!-- /react-text --><span class=\"account-level\">Apprentice</span><br><span class=\"user-details dark\"><!-- react-text: 412 --><!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 413 --> Member since <!-- /react-text --><!-- react-text: 414 -->2016<!-- /react-text --></span></h4></div></div><button class=\"heart light\"><i class=\"fa fa-heart\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i><span class=\"count\">0</span><!-- react-empty: 418 --></button></div><div class=\"description\"><a class=\"descriptionLink\" href=\"#/community/post/3626\"><h3 class=\"title\"><span>Tycho’s Supernova in Cassiopeia</span></h3></a><div class=\"desc\"><p>While out for a stroll on a cool autumn evening in 1572, the great Danish astronomer Tycho Brahe was stopped in his tracks by the sight of a blazing new star in the constellation Cassiopeia.&nbsp; Tycho knew every star in the sky since his youth, and he lived in a time when many believed Aristotle’s&nbsp;pronouncement some &nbsp;2,000 years earlier that the heavens were fixed and unchanging. &nbsp;So a the sudden appearance of a new star was a shocking apparition to Tycho and all stargazers of the day. When he&nbsp;saw this new star, Tycho&nbsp;was, as he later wrote, _“so astonished at this sight that I was not ashamed to doubt the trustworthiness of my own eye.”_\n\n<span id=\"more-3026\"></span>Tycho had no way of knowing the nature of this new star.&nbsp; It would take more than 350 years before astronomers figured out enough physics to understand that Tycho had observed a type of supernovae,&nbsp;a small white dwarf star that suddenly blew itself to bits in a planet-sized nuclear explosion after taking on too much mass from a close companion star.&nbsp; This is known as a Type Ia supernova.\n\nTycho’s supernova grew as bright as the planet Venus and was visible for many weeks during &nbsp;the daytime. The exploding star has long since faded, but there remains in its place a faint nebula in which is embedded an intense source of radio waves and X-rays.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div><ul
